title: Installation was somewhat easy
content: You need to get a lot of stuff out of the way...frozen food, upper and lower drawer and the door to install the replacement ice maker. Simple to screw on and hook up after everything was out of the way. Difficult part was figuring out what wasn’t working. Initially it was a part that was known to fail that caused overflow of water into the bottom of the freezer floor where it froze and then overflowed onto the floor. Then it was the back drain that froze up and had to be thawed out and cleaned out. Next it was trying to figure out why the ice maker stopped working after the overflow problem was fixed. Turned out the ice maker itself failed coincidentally at the same time the other stuff was being fixed. The part was shipped quickly and the installation wasn’t too painful. Then you run it through a few trays of ice (which you throw out) before its ready to use.

author: Albert M

title: Worked as expected, but not real easy to replace due to location of part
content: When I received the part I was worried it wouldn't work, as the start relay was configured differently than the one that came out of the fridge. But, I figured all I could do was try & if i failed then I could always call a repair person. When the fridge stopped working, I went to YTube and watched several videos on what could be wrong. Went ahead & removed the compressor start device and knew right away it was broken. Received the new one & put it in. Because of where the part was located and the cramped quarters in the fridge, it did take some effort to put the new one in. The most difficult part was putting the wire that holds the part in place back. I finally installed it backwards, hooked it on the top first then pushed the bottom portion into place. The fridge started up after I plugged it back in & It got cold within 24 hours.. AS I write this, it turned out this was part 1 of fixing this fridge. It did get cold but it actually got too cold. I ended up also replacing the damper, and now the fridge works great. Finally, the hardest part for me on this repair is: I am 66 yrs old woman & have a bad knee, getting down on the floor, I cushioned myself with an exercise mat, was not comfortable, but I did it and saved myself some $$$ by doing it myself. PartSelect was quick in getting both of the parts I needed out to me in a timely manner.

title: Instant Repairman and Percentages Make it Easy
content: I plugged in my model number into Instant Repairman, I did not have an ice maker, so the next highest percentage was the bi-metal defrost thermostat. I almost also picked the second highest percentage part to save on shipping, but decided to trust the recommended part by Instant Repairman. The actual installation only took about 10 minutes. The moving of the freezer to get access, and defrosting of the frozen water that has accumulated made it into a 60 minute partially active job. The video provided was pretty accurate and I felt it took longer to watch the video than to do the the repair (stopping and starting the video included). Now, everything is working perfectly, I salvaged a 16 year old fridge, spent less than $27 and I am very satisfied with the whole process. Frankly, I have done business with PartSelect before concerning other appliances and it is because Instant Repairman, prices and service are so good. So far I have repaired a double oven, dryer, and two refrigerators.

title: A Little More Than I Expected To Pay But Perfect Fit
content: This is actually Rick’s sister - I’m the one that ordered the part for my brother’s refrigerator. It was already broke and they had it duct taped before I moved in. It fell off again when I was rummaging around in the freezer. (Duct tape will last only so long in a freezer - imagine that!??) Seeing how my brother is a bit frugal - and I say that in the most loving way - in case he reads this?? - I took it upon myself to order a new one. Although it was probably twice as much as I expected to spend, it was the exact part I needed and it fit perfect. He and my sis-in-law were pleased - so thank you! I give you 5 stars - I would give less if I was reviewing the price, but I don’t review like that - that’s on me since I willfully agreed to pay the price you had listed. It was the part I ordered and it fit and I received it in a timely manner, so 5 stars to you for that!

title: Easy Repair OEM replacement part
content: Unplugged the fridge, removed the shelf above and below the ice maker, removed the bail wire, removed the 3 front screws securing the control panel, and removed the control panel. Then used a hair dryer to melt the cubes still in the tray just enough to manually rotate the cube ejector mechanism to vacate the tray. Installed the new control panel secured with 3 screws, replaced the bail wire, replaced the shelves and food, plugged back in. Waited for the water in the tray to freeze and waited for the new control panel to work like a charm.

title: The part worked perfectly!
content: My Whirlpool ice maker and water dispenser both stopped at the same time. I first replaced the water valve of the refrigerator. That did not do the trick. Had I tried removing the filter during diagnostics, I would have found that the water flowed through the filter housing and everything worked fine. When I put the filter back in, all stopped again. I tried replacing the filter, but it still did not work. I cleaned the filter housing with vinegar...still not working. After I ordered and installed the new water filter housing, everything works perfectly again. Somehow the housing had broken and was not able to send water through the filter as it should. Hope this helps you figure out your problem.

title: Quick and Simple
content: The icemaker on my 10-year old refrigerator finally gave up the ghost. I looked on Part Select with the model number found on the inside of the refrigerator, and found that a replacement icemaker was available to fit the model of refrigerator I had. I ordered one, and in less than a week it arrived. Two machine screws later, the old one was off. The new one fit perfectly - although I did have to take it off once to make sure the water line was tucked into the top of the icemaker. After reconnecting the power and the water line at the wall, off it went. It filled immediately, and shortly after that I had ice. A couple weeks later, everything is still working perfectly. DIY is so satisfying, and costs a LOT less than having a service tech fix the exact same problem with a part ordered from Part Select.

title: Simple repair - did it without removing door. Part arrived in 3 days.
content: The video for replacing the door gasket showed removal of both doors - the upper freezer door and the lower fresh food door. If the fridge was not in use (i.e. empty) I would have removed the doors. I left the fridge running and covered the fresh food section opening with a large piece of cardboard I got at the grocery store - found a big cardboard sheet from a pallet of water bottles. Used some masking tape to hold the cardboard cover in place. I suppose you could do without the cardboard cover as food wont spoil in the ~20 mins needed to do gasket replacement. Emptied the door compartments and removed the shelving parts (washed the parts). Removed door panel and replaced gasket - would have been easier with a helper to hold things up, but I did if by myself. Only issue was at bottom of door - the large, thin gasket lip was sagging and interfering with door jamb. Loosened screws to stretch gasket out a bit. Used 3 bits of masking tape to hold up the gasket lip so door closes properly (remove tape after gasket settles into place).

title: All around great stuff
content: This shelf has saved my life. When the last one broke, I was so upset because I had to put all of the stuff like pickles and dressings on another shelf. When the old shelf failed, everything fell on the floor making a big mess. I looked into replacing the shelf only to find out the part was discontinued. I thought I would never find a replacement. However much to my delight the original part was replaced with a different part. I was apprehensive at first because I wasnt sure if this new part would fit my door. I almost decided to just not order a new shelf. To just live with the way my ranch dressing and jelly were haphazardly placed in random places on other shelves. Your website assured me that the part would fit and soothed my fears. I went and threw caution to the wind and took a chance by ordering this new part number. Several days later I recieved the part ordered and apprehensively opened the door to my fridge, afraid I had been deceived by the great internet. Much to my delight it was a perfect fit for the door. I quickly removed all the items that had fallen to the floor when the original shelf broke and replaced them in their rightful place. I want to sincerely thank parts select for their website and the ability to simply order a replacement part for my fridge. Because of them, all is right in the world, and my refrigerator. And Jeffery Epstein didnt kill himself.

title: Quick and Simple
content: The icemaker on my 10-year old refrigerator finally gave up the ghost. I looked on Part Select with the model number found on the inside of the refrigerator, and found that a replacement icemaker was available to fit the model of refrigerator I had. I ordered one, and in less than a week it arrived. Two machine screws later, the old one was off. The new one fit perfectly - although I did have to take it off once to make sure the water line was tucked into the top of the icemaker. After reconnecting the power and the water line at the wall, off it went. It filled immediately, and shortly after that I had ice. A couple weeks later, everything is still working perfectly. DIY is so satisfying, and costs a LOT less than having a service tech fix the exact same problem with a part ordered from Part Select.

content: I have an 11 year old KitchenAid....Beautiful French door refrigerator. First we started to lose temperature in the freezer, Then eventually the refrigerator itself became warm. Kept hearing a clicking sound like the compressor was trying to go on but would not. Read the reviews, and went with the statistical odds, which said to to replace the capacitor first.That DID NOT do the trick. I almost gave up, but then decided to order this compressor start relay. After I installed it and plugged the refrigerator in, I could hear the compressor kick on, and I've been in heaven ever since. I probably saved myself at least 2K for a new refrigerator. I am not the most mechanically inclined guy,but this was sooo easy. I just removed several screws from the back of the refrigerator and removed the old one and plugged it in. It was a simple as that. VERY PLEASED!!

title: Restored Ice Making Function - Video Gave Me Confidence to Do it Myself
content: I had the classic problem of an icicle forming on the short supply "straw" coming out of the back of the unit down to the ice mold on my 20 year old Kitchenaid refrigerator. The only reference on the internet to this problem was here at PartSelect. Installing the part was easy. I do recommend trimming an inch or so of all plastic tubing with a $6 Malida Pipe Tube Hose Cutter -- this assures the o-rings are gripping a virgin section of tube).. The only hard part of the repair was spending an hour flat on the floor vacuuming twenty years worth of dust bunnies under the fridge (you're supposed to vacuum those coils every month right?). After a month of buying ice at the store and putting it in the dispenser drawer what a thrill to see our old ice-maker begin chunking out full trays again. Thank you PartSelect for what you do. You made my family very happy (and me a hero!).

title: The repair that the repairmen didn't want to touch... but it was not a problem.
content: That little clip fixed what we thought was going to be a permanent downgrade to our fridge. Two repairmen didn't want to touch the problem. I'd already changed the water tube (that they didn't want to either), so I figured I'd take a look around at the water dispenser lever that wasn't returning and therefore wasn't shutting off the water. We'd been having to pull the lever back by hand. Like I said, two different repairmen acted like it was experimental brain surgery to fix it. I took a good look, saw that one of the tines on our levers retaining/clip was broken (the one that brings the water lever back, obviously), found it on PartSelect, ordered it, and put it in. It wasn't the easiest job in the world, but it wasn't the hardest either. Why these repairmen were afraid of it baffles me. Aren't the supposed to have the know-how? Anyway, I replaced the clip, and the lever comes back to the proper place, shuts off like it's supposed to, and we're happy as hell!

After confirming the heating element was OK, I removed the thermostat switch that controlled it, and did a diagnostic and confirmed is wasn't closing to turn on the heating element at the prescribed temperature. I click on the link to the Defrost Thermostat switch and found the identical switch, so I ordered it. A couple of days later the part arrived. For grins, I preformed the same diagnostic on the new part to confirm that my test of the old part was correct. I then installed it and reassembled and started the fridge back up, and everything was back to normal.

title: Did the trick and then some.
content: Well my thermostat was going out. This particular fridge has a history of thermostats and relays and starters. Had it fixed under warranty once. Kenmore twice. They have a great program for those not confident in diy. Didn't buy it from them either. Anyhow replaced thermostat and defrost timer about 5 to six years ago myself with parts and instructions from Parts Select. This time around I knew what was up and were to order parts. Ordered a thermostat and defrost timer. There both close together so I do them both. Did the thermostat first, fired it up and on she came. Then did the timer. I want to add for anyone doing the defrost timer. When you first turn your unit back on it may take up to ten minutes or so to kick on. Reason being I believe is your timer might be in a defrost cycle. I had that happen both times to me. Another issue I had was when the fridge kicked on it was really dimming the lights including messing with my window AC units. Also you could hear the starter clicking quite hard. Went ahead and ordered a starter and relay. Didn't have to much in guidance other then find the compressor. There attached to it. Pulled the bottom back panel and there sat the compressor on the left side. Since it had been changed before the spade connections were fine. The starter and relay slide onto prongs coming out of the compressor body. Complete time involved maybe fifteen minutes. Though I did spend another thirty minutes with the vacuum cleaner on the cooling coils. Parts Select sent me 2 relays and starters. Depending on your fridges cubic feet will determine which ones to use. Now the only thing I hear from my 19 year old fridge is the hum of the cooling fan and compressor. Quiet as a mouse and no more blackouts when it kicks on. She still will hit 10 below in the freezer and keeps my fridge between 33 and 32 degrees. I keep it that cold because here in the south especially on weekends the fridge gets opened and closed a bunch. Even after an active day she still stays below 40.Thank you Parts Select.

title: This Fixed My Fridge Problem
content: My fridge was getting warm and the freezer staying cold and it was running non-stop. It was no longer on the normal running on/off cycle. It took me a while to put my finger on it. At first I did a replacement of the defrost timer and that was not it. Same problems after that. Next thing I defrosted all the ice build up that somehow got in the freezer and it ran good for 2 days then back to what it was doing before. I decided to check the defrost thermostat and replace that. As it turns out, the original one malfunctioned and the new part I got here did the trick! The fridge and freezer are running as they should and I might even say better than it was when it was running properly! This part was it! It took about 45 minutes to replace it from start to finish. I'm glad I did this as opposed to spending a few hundred on a new fridge which was obviously not necessary.

title: Proper parts & YouTube = Success !!
content: If your freezer is frosted & the refrigerator is warm this is the repair you need. Actual installation and reassembly was only an hour. YouTube is great - but it does not mention that the worst part is getting the ice to melt. Prior to removing the old parts you must melt the ice that formed on the coils because the old parts failed. Total operation using a heater and a heat gun required 6 hours to complete. This was the second time we performed this replacement since purchase of the appliance 10 years ago. Could it be that they may only last 5 years? Fearing parts will be discontinued, we are about to order an extra set. I think I can do this one more time when at age 76.
author: Joel C

title: My refrigerator is "Cool" again!
content: When I noticed that my refrigerator never seemed to shut off, I found the usual condition that exists when the defrost coils stop auto-defrosting. The freezer was sill freezing, but the refrigerator was getting warmer inside. That indicates that a glacier has formed on the coils in the freezer and the fan can no longer push cold air over into refrigerator side because the ice is blocking the air flow. Removing the panel covering the freezer's coils confirmed my suspicion. So I ordered the replacement defroster "kit" from PS. I asked for expedited delivery and it came without any trouble. Once I had the parts, I proceeded to install them. PS's video instructions are excellent, but I would like to add that you may have to use a hand-held hair dryer to thaw the "glacier" out. Just put a pile of bath towels into the bottom of the freezer to catch the water as the drip pan will easily overflow if you don't. It takes a total of about 1 hour, including defrost time to do the job. PartSelect is a great resource

title: Unnecessary when buying the pan
content: I bought the trim at the same time that I bought the pan because the way that the parts are labeled on the drawing on the PartSelect website, I thought that the pan itself did not come with the trim. Then the trim arrived in the flat package with the shipping label for both items. I needed to pay PartSelect for a second meat pan (doubling down on the irony, as I am a vegan) while the company spent the next week or so processing the refund for the part that never arrived. I was charged a $10 fee for expedited shipping with the guarantee that this fee would be refunded when the order shipped. It was more convenient to do it this way, though had I simply re-ordered the meat pan myself and paid with Amazon Pay as I did the first time, it would have arrived a day sooner. And I would not have needed to call customer service yet again to say that the refund I was given was $3 and not the entire fee of $9.95 that was promised to be refunded. Waiting an extra day on an order that was never shipped or received and paying the extra money for this service did not make sense. On the positive side, the pan, when it did arrive, was just what I needed to replace a drawer that had long before broken in the refrigerator I gave to my parents due to their over-filling and weighing it down. It would have been nice not to need to pay for it twice to receive it once and not to be charged for delivery which was already overdue after the original shipment was covered through Amazon Pay. And it would have been nice to know that you don't buy the trim separately, that they sell the trim separately in case it breaks while the drawer remains intact. I should probably check to make sure all of the refunds went through. No idea why this company keeps offering me opportunities to explain how horrible they are. But I will take them up on the invitations every time.

You pick up all the pieces and you see they can't be glued, Knowing inside you're screwed. You look up Part Select, You find your ancient fridge, They actually have your cap And it only costs a smidge. You send a little money and they ship it really quick. So far it's pretty slick. You call your older kid, He comes from hardy stock. He's just like you back when, He don't need no channel locks. Grabs it with his fingers and he turns it to the right, New cap fit nice and tight. The End

title: Easiest repair yet
content: After finally isolating the frequent, rapid rattling / clicking sound to what appeared to be the damper motor failing, I was happy to find this part in stock and shipped quickly. Super easy repair, all done just inside the refrigerator, so no need to pull it away from the wall or anything. It took more time to take the stuff off the top shelf of the fridge to get ready for the repair than to do the repair itself. Pull off the damper cover with no tools, and just a screw driver to remove the old and install the new--5 minutes, tops. Happy to report it solved the problem and for hundreds less than calling a repair tech to come do this.

title: Damper Control for Kitchenaid refridgerator
content: The damper control on my fridge was becoming excessively noisy when it opened and closed. I Googled the part and found PartSelect. I placed a call and asked if they thought it was, in fact, the Damper. The lady answering the call told me it was the second most common cause of noise for this fridge. The part was delivered in 3 days for less than $80 and I installed it in 10 minutes. The fridge is now silent and working perfectly. Thank you PartSelect, the service was excellent.

title: Easy repair, worked as advertised. Video instruction very helpful.
content: Previous owners had by-passed the water softener, ruining the reverse osmosis water filter supplying water to the refrigerator. This caused fouling and mineral deposits on the freeze tray and nearby components. Final failure appears to have been caused by corrosion of the "U"-shaped heater element that heats up and causes release of the ice cubes, prior to their mechanical ejection by the geared timer motor. Complete disassembly revealed the geared timing motor, the cam-operated electrical contacts, and the normally-open (at room temperature) thermostatic switch were all functional. The only defect in the original ice maker assembly was the heater element. The new part was an exact match for the old part and was installed without difficulty. We had new ice within a few hours and a full ice bucket three days later. Re-installation only required re-using four hex-head, self-tapping, sheet-metal screws and a 1/4-inch hex-head socket driver. Easy peasy.

title: Relatively easy replacement
content: The video that PartSelect shared that showed the repair person replacing the icemaker convinced me I could do the same. I had two issues: separating the electrical connector (it was really tightly held) and the water inlet tube hung up on me when reinstalling the new assembly.That tube has to be pushed up out of the way to allow the icemaker assembly to slide back in. Otherwise, I'm glad I tackled this project and now I have ice again! I can share a bit of advice: if your old icemaker still has ice in it (mine did) but didn't eject it before you decide to make this repair, I suggest wearing a glove while you try and support the assembly while disconnecting the electrical connector. My hand was so cold holding it that I had to set it down and start over.

title: Easy fix, saved me a ton of money calling someone
content: When I went to get water out of my fridge, and heard a "bang", and next thing I knew there was water gushing out of the back of my fridge and my kitchen flooding, I had no idea what was going to be wrong besides the water supply line rupturing. Turns out, thanks to this site and it's very informative reviews and videos, I narrowed it down to this culprit after pulling out the fridge and ensuring the water line was not ruptured. Sure enough, this valve had cracked open at one of the plastic seams and had "exploded" open. VERY easy fix, was the exact replacement part, and I know it saved me A LOT of money from calling a professional to fix something that almost anyone can do. HIGHLY recommend! I have bought many parts from this site before and will continue to do so when needed!

title: Fairly easy for a klutz who had to sit on the floor to do the repair.
content: The part came in a box with no instructions as to how the hoses connected to the inlet part of the valve. Fortunately, there were plenty of online videos that showed exactly how to disconnect the old and reconnect the new. I cut the water line off of the old valve and was left with enough slack in the water line to re-connect to the new one. The new part worked as expected. I kept a paper towel under it for a few days just in case there were leaks (there were none). I did flush the line with about two gallons of water until it ran clear and then re-started the ice machine and all worked well. I'm sure I saved a few hundred dollars in repair bills by doing this myself. I was also glad to find that the old part number exactly matched the replacement (new) part number for my Whirlpool side-by-side refrigerator

Since the three lights are daisy-chained like Xmas lights, it kind of a crap shoot as to which one is "bad". The 2 lights in the fridge are different to the one in the freezer. I went with the recommended part (freezer light}. It was a super quick/simple swap out and fixed the problem immediately. The one thing I love about PartSelect is the tutorials. author: Kathy S

title: Easy repair LED Light
content: The LED light came in seal package. It was easy to install. You will need a very small size flat head screw driver to pop the light out of its slot. You might want to shut the power off to the refrigerator first. Discount the connector . Plug the new LED light into the connector and pop it back into its slot. Turn the power on. On a side note if when you open the refrigerator or freezer door and the lights are constantly blinking . One of LEDs (there are 4 tiny lights in the tube or circuit) is probably out. There are two lights in the refrigerator side and one in the freezer side . You will have to look really carefully to see which circuit in the LED is out.

title: The right Parr for the repair
content: On the morning of July 3rd, as I opened the refrigerator door of my 2 year old Whirlpool side-by-side the door came off as the pin in the hinge popped out. I was able to pop the pin in but it kept popping out. So I called Parts Select. The representative did a great job of choosing the correct part. And I paid an extra shipping fee but the part still took 2 weeks to arrive at my door. Then I found that I needed special tools to install the part. Meanwhile thevpin kept popping out. So I had to hold the pin down with my right hand as I opened or closed the door with my right hand. Of my 2 year-old fridge. Then I spent an hour at my Local Lowes where I had purchased the fridge to replace my 5 year old Samsung. In June 2023bi bought an extended warranty but the salesperson had not provided the paperwork with my warranty number and I didn't notice until I needed this part installed. So I finally had the part that I bought and a date for the part to be installed. And the repair person told me that they have to replace these hinges all the time. So Parts Select dud a great job. But the shipping company wasn't worth the extra cost. And it appears that Whirlpool appliances are no longer reliable no matter how much they cost. I recommend Parts Select when you need something. They are great.

title: Part fits fine. Working well. But ...
content: Removing the old clamps and installing the new ones was the most difficult part of swapping out my Whirlpool dryer motor. More of a pain than cutting off the old blower wheel with a Dremel. Tore-up one clamp trying to remove it. I was unable to get the screw driver removal and install techniques shown on the video (and other videos on the internet) to work. Motor clamps didn't want to come off the failed motor or go on the replacement motor. Ended up slip forcing/pushing them on from the side after hooking them on either end first. I would suggest on your video telling folks if they're looking to replace a dryer motor, they are probably dealing with a 20+ year old machine. Check on Mod. No. label or manufacturer's website for build date. If you're dealing with a machine that old purchase a blower wheel and a couple of motor clamps along with the motor. Don't even bother with the effort and cussing necessary to round off the blower wheel plastic nut with a 13/16 wrench, adjustable wrench or Vice Grips. Immediately remove the back of the dryer and the plumbing to expose the wheel and cut it off with a Dremel. My Whirlpool had to be tilted forward from behind to snake out the plumbing. Wouldn't suggest using a chisel unless it's a sharp one. Would take a lot of effort chiseling a hole in the center of the blower wheel which is molded from a of pretty stout piece of plastic. Despite the difference between the wiring of the failed and replacements motors, have faith. Follow the instructions provided with the new motor and it’ll all work out in the end. Hint, do not lose the two 1/8” wire blades provided. You’ll more than likely need them. Have a heat gun or hair dryer at the ready to heat the shrink wrap. Hints for more humanely removing and installing the motor clamps? I have no idea. Disappointed, but not surprised, my genuine Whirlpool dryer motor was made in Mexico.

title: Simple repair, correct parts, fast shipping, best price.
content: Part was received in a sealed Whirlpool bag, and looked just like the one I needed to replace. The fan had stopped working in the freezer, and this was leading to frost build up in both the freezer and refrigerator. If the air can't move, the fridge can't cool down. I just needed to remove 2 screws at the bottom of the rear panel, and lift it up. You will need a screwdriver to lift the latch on the old connector plugged in the back wall. With the connector unplugged, there is no power in any of the wires, so you safety can swap all the smaller connectors to the new harness. Note the location of the temperature sensor and clip the new one in the same place and wrap the sticky tape back around it. Once the fan, ground wire, and heater are connected, just snap the main connecter into the back wall. Put the rear panel back in place and reinstall the 2 screws at the bottom.

title: Happy ending to refrigerator repair
content: I ordered a control board on Dec 5, 2020, and specified the ordinary shipping method. PartSelect said that the part usually would reach me in about 3 days. The control board arrived in good condition, however; I installed it immediately and after 3 weeks I'm glad to say that it's doing well. Some footnotes...the board's wrapper said ESD and once I unplugged my refrigerator, I had no nearby ground to touch, so I discharged myself before I unplugged and hoped that touching the refrigerator while installing the board would be good enough. Also, I read the return policy and it says that customers are responsible for return postage. If PartSelect had sent me a bad board, I would be very angry about that policy.

title: Easy Repair - So far seems to be the right part.

When I searched on PartSelect for what the problem may be, they said 99% chance it's the Thermo Fuse Assembly. I liked those odds. It's been about 2 weeks now since I made the repair. The fridge is maintaining its temperature so far. Previously, it would have started getting warmer by now. If it maintains temp for another week, I'll know for sure that the problem is solved.

title: Easy repair and part works!
content: The water line from the input valve on my Kenmore fridge to the water filter for the icemaker/water dispenser has been giving me trouble springing leaks for a couple years but I was unable to find the correct replacement tube online. Therefore, I had to purchase and install a connector multiple times at the leak area (which eventually leaked themselves) as a band aid. I even ordered a replacement tube about a year ago after speaking with a sales rep to find the right one, but of course it was not. So more band aids. And the diagrams provided online to determine the part you need are horrible! They are very small and when you try to zoom in the determine the part identification number they get blurry. But this time I was able to determine the correct tube and it's working like a charm! The shipping cost was about as much and the tube itself so it doubled the total cost. That and the struggle to determine the correct part are the reasons I did not give it 5 stars.

title: pretty easy repair
content: the three hinges on a samsung double-door fridge have a tendency to break if the door is slammed with the air barrier in the open position. I've replaced bottom hinge twice, top hinge twice, and center hinge and heater cover once. Fortunately You Tube has several videos about the process. The first times I did the hinges I remover the vertical part and did the repair on the range. The last time I disassembled it all in place and did it (with occasional beeping to remind me that the door was open) in place. Easier to do it in place. Tools required: Duct tape, small flat head screwdriver of butter knife. If I can do it, you can do it too.

title: Should be an easy repair! Basic part! Ten year old refrigerator!
content: The ice mold is a basic part, brand new, factory packaged. Swapped out old one easily by watching video. Waited 24 hours and had ice in the mold but no harvesting to the ice bucket. Checked thermostat with a hair dryer and ice harvested (melted ice enough to be pushed into the bucket, thermostat was working but mold was not heating). Disassembled the icemaker, checked aluminastic was covering thermostat. Then slightly bent pins on motor plug for positive contact with wiring harness. Over next two days the ice mold heated and the infrared switch lights indicated harvesting mode but ice extraction arm would not rotate to push ice out of mold. I replugged the refrigerator several times during the two days and finally everything was working normal the morning of the third day. I surmised using the hairdryer got things out of sync. Just a typical week of DIY repairs. Partselect helps greatly with videos and other customers' letters of experiences.

author: DANIEL P

title: Fast delivery
content: When initially shopping for this part, this site was more expensive than others, so I ordered the (in stock) part overnight from there; who wouldn't want to save $50? Well, I waited 4 days, still hadn't received it and called. They assured me it'd be there within two days. That didn't happen, so I called again. This nonsense carried on for 3 WEEKS before I ordered from here. Three weeks without a refrigerator, living out of a cooler, and replacing ice regularly, is a LONG time. I got the part overnight, less than 24 hours from ordering from PartSelect, and promptly cancelled my order from the other site. They sent the part a week after I cancelled my order, with overnight shipping, and now consider the order fulfilled. They're still making it extremely difficult to get a refund. I would order from here again in a heartbeat; it may be more expensive, but I spent more than what I saved on ice while waiting for the discounted part from the other site.

title: Works as expected
content: Instructions were clear. The only issue I had was after installation, the element was not heating. After further research, I discovered I needed to run the dishwasher in diagnostic mode. For my model: by pressing any 3 (three) keys in the 1-2-3-1-2-3-1-2-3 sequence except Start, Delay, or Cancel – make sure the delay between key presses is not more than 1 sec. In some cases, you have to press button #2 then shut the door to begin the service cycle (Don’t forget the diagnostics cycle starts once you close the door). Credit goes to: https://machinelounge.com/whirlpool-dishwasher-diagnostic-mode/

For my model: by pressing any 3 (three) keys in the 1-2-3-1-2-3-1-2-3 sequence except Start, Delay, or Cancel – make sure the delay between key presses is not more than 1 sec. In some cases, you have to press button #2 then shut the door to begin the service cycle (Don’t forget the diagnostics cycle starts once you close the door). Credit goes to: https://machinelounge.com/whirlpool-dishwasher-diagnostic-mode/

title: Correct Part, Video Helped
content: The long plastic end of one of the cables seen in the photo broke on our 14-yr-old KitchenAid dishwasher. It connects a tensioner spring that assists with opening and closing the door. Even though the cable & spring on the other side was still intact, the door would slam down when opened. Did some research, found this kit. With the help of the video, got it fixed. Would appreciate if the video covered removing dishwashers bolted to the sides of the surrounding cabinet (as in our case due to a granite countertop) and the positioning of the kickplate/skirt on reassembly (is it supposed to sit flush with the floor? It was not when we removed it). Getting the dishwasher out took the most time. The repair itself went quickly and was not difficult. Sorry no photo because it is hidden from view. 5 stars for helping us avoid a costly technician visit. I'm a repeat customer and will be back again.

title: Works as expected
content: Instructions were clear. The only issue I had was after installation, the element was not heating. After further research, I discovered I needed to run the dishwasher in diagnostic mode. For my model: by pressing any 3 (three) keys in the 1-2-3-1-2-3-1-2-3 sequence except Start, Delay, or Cancel – make sure the delay between key presses is not more than 1 sec. In some cases, you have to press button #2 then shut the door to begin the service cycle (Don’t forget the diagnostics cycle starts once you close the door). Credit goes to: https://machinelounge.com/whirlpool-dishwasher-diagnostic-mode/

title: My brand new 17-yr old Superba
content: We built our house in late 2000. We installed a Whirlpool Superba Dishwasher which has always run flawlessly. Recently, the soap dispenser door began to fail to lock shut and the top rack wasn't drying very well. After going online and locating the parts, I called PartSelect to confirm that the legacy repair parts would be compatible with my older, NLA dishwasher. The phone support/sales agent was fantastic and recommended the appropriate parts. I ordered on the call and got my parts 2 days later. In the email confirming that the parts had shipped were links to videos showing the installation procedures. I followed both instructions and completed both repairs in about an hour, including cleaning up 17 years worth of goop behind and around both pieces. I know have sparkling, dry dishes when I open the dishwasher. it's like a new machine, for about 15% of the cost of buying one. I couldn't be happier.

title: Exactly what was needed.
content: Started to get a little bit of water leaking from the lower section of the washer unit during cycles. Upon inspection, noted that the lower gasket looked frayed right where the wheels of the lower basket roll out on. Which means of course it will eventually do it again, but hopefully not anytime soon. Installation of this new gasket solved the leak right away. There's a little work to install it, but nothing too major. Just have to detach the door at the hinges, and disconnect the tension cables from the door (easy). Slide the old gasket out (may take some pulling), and then slide the new one in its place. Be sure to install it in the same orientation that the old one was. It's not difficult to see which way is which. Reverse the steps to reattach the door, and done. NOTE: THIS GASKET 100% FITS GE MODEL GDF520PSD0SS

One review said they purchase a Gasket tub Plastic (part no. PS11721489) and a door gasket (part no. PS11700870). I found a video describing how to do ithttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cmu5jljVDdU. The parts were under $20 and probably save my daughter at least 10 times that to do the job myself. Thank you PartSelect!!

title: easy repair and cheap fix
content: As other reviews mentioned this part solved the majority of the leak. I was getting a little leak along the door rubber due to the door being slightly warped from bent hinges and door opening all the way to the floor. I am planning to remodel and replace the unit in the near future so I did not want to spend the $120 so I flipped the rubber over and it created a tight seal. It seems sense the door only makes contact to the rubber on a thin center line so the edges were still thick and firm enough to make a seal. I know this is not the solution but it is a temporary quick fix that is working like a charm.

title: Gasket and Gasket Insert Replacement
content: A simple job once the caked dishwasher detergent leftovers are cleaned off the bottom of the door liner and in the corner "gutters" of the dishwasher body. The help video's suggestion of putting the gasket in the clothes dryer for a few minutes was a good one (and one I'll no doubt be using again with other jobs using similar materials - much more convenient than putting the piece in hot water). No reason not to attempt this job - just keep some tension on the gasket as you insert it from the top middle and down the side in order to be sure to have enough to overlap the gasket insert's gap sufficiently when you get to the middle of the bottom of the door.

title: The part arrived fairly quickly and the repair was not too difficult.
content: After ordering the part it came within three days. It is a factory part and is as advertised. The online video that showed how to install the part did not mention that the part has three plastic tabs that have to be inserted underneath three metal tabs that are at the bottom of the diswasher inner door. I had to tightly hold the part against the inner door and use a small flat head screw driver to press the plastic tab underneath the metal door tabs. If you do not have a magnitized nut driver then you should get one as the screws are very difficult to reinstall without one. Also, use a small block of wood to hold up the panel that covers the screw heads while you are reinstalling them RLH

content: As other reviews mentioned this part solved the majority of the leak. I was getting a little leak along the door rubber due to the door being slightly warped from bent hinges and door opening all the way to the floor. I am planning to remodel and replace the unit in the near future so I did not want to spend the $120 so I flipped the rubber over and it created a tight seal. It seems sense the door only makes contact to the rubber on a thin center line so the edges were still thick and firm enough to make a seal. I know this is not the solution but it is a temporary quick fix that is working like a charm.

title: "Piece of Cake!"
content: This part was quite easy to place, after removing the old gasket and using a Clorox wipe to thoroughly clean the groove it fits into. I just marked the midpoint and lined it up, then pressed it into place. The only thing that was a bit messy was wiping off all the oily good they coat it with. My advice is twofold, mark the midpoint of the gasket and use less grease. Since it's sealed in an airtight bag, less grease will be enough, it won't evaporate.

title: GE Dishwasher Drain Pump
content: Drain pump on dishwasher died. Ordered a new one from parts direct and it somewhat fixed issue. Water was still coming out slow. So after running one complete cycle with no dishes or soap, we took a small drain cleaner tool and ran it into nozzle end of hose. Turned out that there were small seeds(like from corned beef) and other debris stuck in knozzle. Ran dishwasher again, no dishes or soap, and when water started coming out it was much stronger and more debris washed out. Apparently debris broke original pump. Replacement and cleaning of nozzle fixed issue. Would definitely use parts direct again. Replacement pump came within 3 days.

content: Subject: RETURN PART# PS1524989 Order # 10751239 I just received my part, water inlet tubing and it is 25.5 inches long. The trouble is the hose it was designed to replace is 27 inches. The inch and a half shortage doesn't allow for the ends to go all the way on the inlet ends and even if you try just putting them on half way it still forces the hose to flatten around the lower "bend" which would cut off the water from getting any further up the hose. To have this hose not the exact same length is ridiculous. Unless this hose was just a miscut that didn't get caught by quality control and you check to measure a new one for the correct length , Frigidaire needs to correct this issue. As I can't wait for that to happen I need to effect a return of this item.

Yesterday I talked with a very nice lady (Joanne) she has reordered the part from Calf. It is to be shipped in a box rather than a very thin padded envelope. content: My 14 year old Ge dishwasher was leaking from the drain valve shaft every time the solenoid went into drain mode. My dishwasher was not installed properly so this repair was very frustrating with the wires and water supply line in the way. The old seal had a lip side seal on both sides, this one only had one. I replaced this seal along with the push on nut and a new solenoid assembly, the old one was covered in a dry soapy mess. After reinstalling everything the dishwasher did not leak. The push on nut and shaft seal should really be included with solenoid assembly kit.

title: Installing The Pump Connector on a GE Dishwasher
content: Installing The Pump Connector (part # PS259530) On a GE Dishwasher After disconnecting and removing the dishwasher, lay the dishwasher on its back. Loosen the clamp (332) between the pump connector and the pump motor. Next loosen the clamp (452) between the pump and the sump. Disconnect the part (420) from the pump motor and remove the pump motor from pump connector and the sump. Next turn the pump connector to the left to unscrew it from the bottom of the dishwasher. You may need pliers or adjustable wrench to turn the pump connector. In reverse order repeat the process to reinstall components. Takes about 30 min start to finish.

title: Easy repair took an hour start to finish
content: The part was an easy repair . Only one slight problem was the end of the shaft of the new part was round where as the original had a flat side half moon shape at the tip. Inside the mount the hole was shaped the same way so that the shaft goes in only one way. So i just a small flat file to match shape the new part to the old. And carefully lined up the hole with the flat spot on the shaft and the part went right in. I tested the machine twice on full heavy and regular cycles. No leaks, no noises, no issues. Machine is repaired. I can only figure that the dishwasher being 6 years old had a replacement design on newer models. Either way it was an easy repair took about an hour.

title: For a person who knows next to nothing about repair, this was a super easy fix!
content: First, it should be noted that my repair knowledge is/was minimal prior to ordering these wheels. Now, a piece of advice from a novice: Take the extra few seconds to plug your model number in at the start to avoid ordering the wrong items and shipping things back. Yup ... did that because "Of course I know which part I needed" ... I didn't. Thankfully the customer service people are phenomenal and helped fix my confusion, aka teach me to read the suggestion of putting in my model number before ordering. As far as ordering and replacement goes, a suggestion from me. If your wheel(s) wore out naturally and you are thinking of ordering 1 of these ... DON'T. Save yourself the shipping costs and order 4 of these from the get-go. Disregard if it isn't general wear that caused your wheel to fail. Best practice in removal of the old wheel (to prevent you from injuring your hand ... like me ....) use a flathead screwdriver or other punch type tool and a hammer or mallet to break off the 2 locking buttons holding the wheel in place. Attempting to pry them back, while pushing the wheel casing out was a bit of a failure on my part. When putting the new wheels in, it was as simple as just snapping them in place and done. The wheels work wonderfully!

title: A snap to replace. No, really!
content: It was a matter of snap-snap-snap to replace the part on my dishwasher. I had to fiddle with the bad one to get it loose, but worked it out, and it seems to have the additional benefit of leaving cleaner dishes. After disconnecting the electronic control jumper, you have to reach down under the inside of the machine and uncouple the fastener ring inside. (That's what I had to figure out. Make sure to have a careful grasp of the ring, or you will have to fish it out of the cess pit at the bottom of the machine.) Lift the old part out, drop the new one in, and secure it with the ring in the exact opposite process. It just snaps into place. Reconnect the control jumper, and it's done.

title: When your upper tray slides off the front end of one of the rails, this part will fix the problem.
content: If the old rail is still on the rollers in the cubicle, just grab it firmly and twist it up and down off the rollers. Transfer the rear plastic stop block which they did not include for some for unknown reason. NOTE: this is the only thing wrong with the product, because the rear plastic stop block is not easy to release and transfer to the new rail. Once I had finally completed the transfer I said to myself, "the rear plastic stop block won't survive another trip like that, I'll have to buy another dishwasher or use a screw". Yes, this is the best solution you're going to get. -Chris

title: It worked; I had to wire it up differently for my kenmore
content: The wires on the thermistor were fried. Apparently, the thermistor failed as it was burnt/smoked. It was difficult to remove the white plastic from the circuit board holder. One removed wire went down underneath the dishwasher; instructions left it hanging; also had the board connection hanging so I checked with an inline amp meter between the two hanging wires and got 250mA as the washer lit up. So I tied these together and all was good. I read the instructions and what I did was different. I lucked out !! 4 stars becasue instructions do not address the two hanging wires. Need to include a wirenut.

MIKE B

title: Easy repair, outrageous price
content: I did both a dishwasher door seal and the bottom (lower door) seal replacement. Both worked fine, were easy to do, and the video instructions were helpful. The Lower door seal REQUIRES the silicon glue stuff - or the seal won't stay in place. I did not use the two overflow cups...and their replacement would have been much more work. (remove the door and potentially have to pull the dishwasher out of the cabinet to reach the door springs.) The bottom line: everything worked and my dishwasher is now usable. The bad part? These seals were incredibly expensive. The markup had to be at least 1000%...and I'm not exaggerating. I'm sure I needed about 30" of gasket, and they wheeled 30" off of a spool, cut it, and stuck it in a bag and mailed it to me. Their cost couldn't have been $4...and I paid almost $70. The door seal kit was even worse. Was it cheaper than buying a new dishwasher? Yep. Would I do it again? I don't think so.

title: Thread lock was a problem
content: I received the parts for my dishwasher repair quickly. When I pulled the dishwasher out of the cabinet to install the new heating element I encountered a problem with the new element. It seems they've applied a liquid thread locking compound to the threaded part of the element. the material was applied much too thick and would not allow the nuts that retain the element and seal the rubber washer to thread onto the element stem. I had to re-thread the element stem to remove the red thread locking compound and subsequently re-thread the plastic retaining nuts to match. I was then able to install the element, however this made the process considerably difficult and frustrating. If a person did not have the ability to effectively modify the element as I did I have no idea how they would have installed the part.

title: Easy Repair
content: I just needed 4 tiny parts that had worn out on my old portable dishwasher, These were little white plastic clips that moved in and out in the connector to my faucet. They're about the size of a clipped fingernail, but they keep the hose attached to the faucet. I bet the 4 of them cost less than a penny to make. Instead of being able to buy just those 4 tiny pieces of plastic, I was forced to buy a whole new hose assembly. When I received the hose assembly, I removed the 4 tiny pieces of plastic from the new hose assembly, and placed them into the old one. The dishwasher has worked perfectly since then. I'm just upset that I had to spend almost $90 to buy a whole new hose. To me, it's like I needed a new stem for an auto tire with very little tread wear, but I was forced to buy a whole new tire. But I guess if I ever need a new hose, I've got one.

title: worked as expected
content: I was able to receive a drain pump for my Maytag Dishwasher after getting a code that it was not working and could not get the washer to drain. The installation was very quick once I resolved that none of the drain lines were plugged and I had localized the problem. The unit can be easily replaced by disconnecting power, and pulling out the dishwasher from the counter. The insulation will have to be set aside for later use and the insulation near the pump pulled back to expose the assembly. By tipping the machine on its side the pump can be clearly seen. Taking the new pump, I removed the power source and immediately attached to the new pump. I then twisted the old pump out from its seating, and notices that one blade in the pump had broken and jammed the existing unit. Taking out the small piece of metal, I when again checked hoses to be sure no blockage and tightened new pump into place, The process only takes a few minutes if this is the problem. After install, put back the insulation covering the pump assembly and upright the machine. Then replace insulation cover and slide back into counter. Once in place connect the power and it should run fine. We had no error code once the machine was turned on. Hope this helps a bit if you have a similar issue. Be sure to check all your hoses prior to replacement as this is a more common problem.

title: Easy Installation - Rev-J Shows Whirlpool Issues
content: Installation of Rev-J of the part was quick and simple. If you are replacing this part because the solenoid struggles to actuate the soap/rinse agent dispensing, look for goo in the slide assembly located at the end of the solenoid. If present, this is rinse agent that has leaked out and is acting like glue. Remove the power source, tape the area off in a manner that allows you to contain water flow and rinse the slide assembly with hot water. The goo will dissolve quickly and the slide will move freely.

title: Works great, easy to install but i didn't need it.
content: I had a small leak and thought it was the gasket or possibly cracked plastic. I installed this kit and it works as intended. However my leak did not stop. Upon closer inspection the leak was originating from inside and small bubbles were flowing down the inside of the float switch tube out the bottom. I discovered this is due to using too much soap/detergent. I changed from using the little shrink wrapped cakes to old school pour out of the spout granular detergent and the leaks stopped. Consider this if you have a leak your trying to stop.

title: Simple repair and appliance back in service
content: I was prepared to buy a new dishwasher to replace my Kenmore, which stopped working several months ago, when I discovered the PartSelect site. I read some of the reviews and comments and gleaned a good deal of diagnostic information from the site. Since the old touch pad was in very bad shape and only one light would still work, I suspected this was the main problem. So I ordered a new touch pad, and for good measure, a new thermal control switch; total expenditure $160. The parts arrived a couple of days later, I disassembled the touch pad and replaced both parts. The machine fired right up, thus saving me about $600 more dollars for a new machine. I subsequently ordered touch-up paint/coating and plastic bumper tips for the two rusted baskets, which I hope will be serviceable for another year or two. Machine now works fine again.

title: Moving a dishwasher
content: All the videos on how to install this cable explain that you need to remove the two screws that attach the dishwasher to under the counter and then pull the dishwasher out to get to the cable. What NONE of them mentioned was that on my GE dishwasher, inside on the frame, there are two stainless steel caps covering two more screws that hold the dishwasher into the cabinets on either side. I thought the dishwasher was just heavy or perhaps stuck to the floor and pulled hard on the dishwasher and ended up cracking the sides of the cabinets where those two side screws were. So my advice is to look for those stainless steel caps on the front inside the dishwasher, remove them and take out the additional screws.

title: Replace dishwasher door panel
content: I wanted to replace the black panel with stainless steel for a kitchen renovation. The new panel arrived with no damage. Although there were no instructions provided for replacing the panel, it was pretty straightforward. The operating panel at the top of the door also had to be detached from the door. When removing the operating panel with the door panel, be sure the support it well to not damage the wiring between the door and the operating panel. There is a wiring connector that needs to be unplugged from the door to the operating panel. Once the wiring is disconnected, you can remove the operating panel from the door panel and then attach the new panel to the operating panel, then reverse the disassembly process.

title: Avoiding Future Problems
content: The cause of the problem with our 14 year old Kenmore gas dryer was the coils on the gas valve which have been replaced with your parts and the dryer works correctly now. However, I decided to replace the radiant flame sensor, which was easy to install, the igniter, the thermal fuse, the thermal cut-off fuse and the internal bias thermostat at the same time to reduce the chances of future problems. Essentially everything electrical that controls the gas valve and flame have now been replaced. We will see in 3-4 years if this was time and money well spent as we plan to replace both the dryer and washer at that time. Very pleased with the quality of parts and prompt delivery of the three recent orders for the above plan. Best regards, Fred.

title: Repairing gas dryers are fun and easy!
content: So, we were not sure of what parts we needed so we ordered a surplus of what we actually needed. It turned out to be the squirrel cage fan nut was - is cracked so the fan wobbled and made a unknowingly sound. Another problem was the left rubber wheel bearing was already bad, and made another squeaky noise, so we change that. It now runs smooth and quiet. If you have my records you see we had some problems like this last year and replace the belt and the two rubber wheels that hide the drum. Thanks

title: Incredible Experience. Seriously.
content: Ok so this was the first time I've used PartSelect. My old dryer bit the dust, but with my son going to college in a month, it's a good time to pinch pennies. So I decided to try to fix it myself. I finally found PartSelect and holy crap, yall! What a great experience. It was so easy to find the right parts that I needed, the prices were way less than MFG-direct, and when my parts arrived, I got an email with a freaking walkthru video of the repair for each of the three parts! So satisfyingly easy. The crazy thing is my washer just bit the dust too. Murphy's law. Normally I'd be irked that my washer broke a week after fixing the dryer. But I'm actually kinda pumped because I get to do another round on PartSelect. My wife will really think I'm Bob Vila if I can go 2 for 2 lol. Well done yall. UX thru the roof.
